-- Regression: Iron_Ident cast in leak statement without kind check.
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 65 AUDIT-01 row 9 (M-severity) flagged
-- src/analyzer/escape.c (leak-statement RC detection branch) for casting
-- ls->expr to (Iron_Ident *) without a preceding kind check.
-- expr_ident_name returns non-NULL for both Iron_Ident and the root of
-- an Iron_FieldAccess chain, so the downstream checks `id->resolved_sym`
-- and `id->resolved_type` were reading the FieldAccess::object field
-- offset — silently wrong whenever the leak target was a chained
-- expression like `leak wrapper.inner` rather than a bare identifier.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.**
--   Iron_Ident:       [span][kind][resolved_type][name][resolved_sym][constraint_name]
--   Iron_FieldAccess: [span][kind][resolved_type][object][field]
--
--   The shared prefix is {span, kind, resolved_type} (enforced by
--   PROT-01 _Static_assert). `resolved_sym` in Iron_Ident overlaps
--   `field` in Iron_FieldAccess — a char* reinterpret of the downstream
--   object pointer. Reading `id->resolved_sym->type` then dereferences
--   what is actually an Iron_Node pointer as an Iron_Symbol, producing
--   wrong type-kind comparisons in the RC-detection pass.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** escape.c (leak handler) now checks
-- ls->expr->kind == IRON_NODE_IDENT BEFORE the Iron_Ident cast and calls
-- IRON_NODE_ASSERT_KIND on the guarded path. The non-ident path
-- (field-access leak target that doesn't match any heap binding) falls
-- through to the existing "not a heap-allocated value" diagnostic with
-- is_rc=false, which is the correct error shape for a non-ident leak.
-- PROT-04 walkthrough safety net (M-severity site), Phase 66 Plan 03.
-- The remaining 25 M-severity AUDIT-01 rows are covered by Plan 05.
--
-- **Severity.** M. Affects `leak` statements whose target is a
-- field-access chain rather than a bare identifier. Blast radius
-- smaller than H sites because the wrong resolved_sym usually produced
-- a downstream undefined-symbol error rather than a crash, but the
-- wrong RC-type classification silently misclassified leak diagnostics.

object Point {
    var x: Int
    var y: Int
}

func main() {
    val p = heap Point(3, 4)
    println("before leak: {p.x} {p.y}")
    -- Positive path: leak on a bare ident that IS a heap binding.
    -- Exercises the leak handler all the way through to
    -- find_heap_for_name returning non-NULL; the new IRON_NODE_ASSERT_KIND
    -- gate guards the negative path where is_rc detection runs.
    leak p
}
